    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but i've been hearing a lot about people saying originalism is just a way for certain judges to push their own politics instead of actually following the law. is there any scholarly merit to that critique, or is it just a way to dismiss the theory?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This critique does have some scholarly merit and is a significant part of the debate on originalism. Critics argue that originalism can be used merely as a guise for judges' personal preferences, especially when these preferences align with a more conservative or libertarian rhetoric. They point out that the original understanding of the Constitution was reached by a limited group of predominantly elite men, which could lead to interpretations that don't reflect contemporary societal values deemed fair or just. Both proponents and critics of originalism agree that it's essential for judges to uphold the rule of law, but they sharply disagree about whether adhering to the original meaning upholds this principle. As a student, examining these contrasting viewpoints can deepen your understanding of the complex nature of constitutional interpretation. Does that address your doubts?",
      "source": "target",
